answers.body_markdown:
You have created a functional interface `Predicate` whose method is declared to throw an `InterruptedException`, which is a checked exception.  However, you call `test()` in the body of a lambda expression as the parameter to [the `Thread` constructor that takes a `Runnable`][1], whose [`run()` method is not declared to throw any checked exceptions][2].  Therefore, because the exception is not caught in the body, a compiler error occurs.

[1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Thread.html#Thread-java.lang.Runnable-
[2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Runnable.html#run--

Incidentally, it may be confusing to name your own interface `Predicate`, because of the [built-in functional interface `java.util.function.Predicate`][3] whose functional method returns a `boolean`.

[3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/function/Predicate.html

Because `run()` can&#39;t throw an `Exception`, you must `catch` the exception and handle it.  You might log the exception and its stack trace.  You might wrap the exception in a `RuntimeException`.  Either way, catching the checked exception will allow the code to compile.  Example:

    Thread t1 = new Thread(() -&gt; {
        try {
            prod.test();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            // handle: log or throw in a wrapped RuntimeException
            throw new RuntimeException(&quot;InterruptedException caught in lambda&quot;, e);
        }
    });

As @rgettman says, the name `Predicate` is unhappy... Anyways, you could take advantage of `default` methods in Java:

    interface PredicateButPleaseChangeMyName {

        void test() throws InterruptedException;

        default void tryTest() {
           try {
              this.test();
           } catch (InterruptedException e) {
              // handle e (log or wrap in a RuntimeException)
           }
        }
    }

Then, in your main method, simply create the threads by calling the default `tryTest()` method:

    Thread t1 = new Thread(() -&gt; prod.tryTest());
    Thread t2 = new Thread(() -&gt; cons.tryTest());

If you intend on running a single method only with no arguments you can replace the lambda with a method reference.

For instance:

    Thread t = new Thread(() -&gt; {
			foo();
		});

can be more succinctly expressed as 

    Thread t = new Thread(this::foo);

To start it

    t.start();

