1.

I personally don&#39;t feel that it is an anti-pattern.  Your callMethodFromAbstractClass() method can be any helper method that extenders of ClassA want to reuse (or even override).  Imagine if instead it were normalizeDataFragment(String fragment).  Rather than have all of the classes having to know how to normalize a fragment, you have it in the abstract class, and then as the classes process the data, they can use it if/when they need to, or even override/extend it if desired.

2.

You don&#39;t Autowire classes, but rather instances of classes.  So, if you configure an instance of ClassB, and you want to autowire it into another class, you can use either ClassA or ClassB to autowire it:

    @Autowired
    private ClassA classA;

    @Autowired
    private ClassB classB;

Either will work, and will get a reference to your instance of ClassB, because from spring&#39;s perspective (and Java&#39;s), an instance of ClassB is both valid as an instance of ClassA and ClassB.

To create the instance itself, if using Java config, you would simply make a bean within your @Configuration class and instantiate it like you want.

    @Bean
    public ClassA classBWithSomeData() {
      return new ClassB(&quot;somedata&quot;);
    }

